<article>
    <h1>Meidi-Ya</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210103/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-03"><time>2021-01-03</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Where: 01-65, 01-51 to 01-56, 02-26 to 36 Mil­lenia Walk, 9 Raf­fles Boule­vard; open: 10am to 10pm daily Info: Call 6339-1111 or go to www.meidi-ya.com.sg/en</p>
    <p>Since its open­ing six weeks ago, Meidi-Ya’s two­s­torey flag­ship store at Mil­lenia Walk has been abuzz with land­locked shop­pers crav­ing a taste of Ja­pan.</p>
    <p>The first floor fea­tures an 88-seat cafe and bar, as well as Kobe bak­ery Gokoku, which has a small dine-in sec­tion.</p>
    <p>Make a bee­line for the Naka­jima sushi counter – where fresh fish is di­rectly im­ported by Naka­jima Suisan, the largest fish sup­plier in Ja­pan. Or check out the lat­est snacks from Hokkaido at the Hokkaido Dosanko Plaza sec­tion.</p>
    <p>The su­per­mar­ket on the se­cond floor fea­tures an ex­ten­sive range of fresh Ja­panese fruit, veg­eta­bles and fish, as well as Kobe beef and Kurobuta pork. Stock up on items such as the Kubara Ago­dashi soup base ($7.20) for steam­boat; Nip­pun Pre­mium frozen pasta ($8.80); Uma­jimura Yuzu Sushi­nomoto (yuzu sushi vine­gar, $12.80); and Chak­ouan Imaricha Macha-iri (green tea leaves, $18).</p>
    <p>Do not miss the se­lec­tion of house-made tofu (from $2.20), soya milk ($2.30) and abura age (Ja­panese fried tofu pouch, $2.95). The in-house brand also fea­tures fresh jam, syrups and sauces that are im­ported from Ja­pan.</p>
    <p>Sake lovers can head to the liquor store – op­po­site Meidi-Ya’s duplex – for sake, whisky and wine.</p>
    <p>Mr Nagoshi Shuji, manag­ing di­rec­tor of Meidi-Ya Sin­ga­pore, notes the “ever-grow­ing de­mand for pre­mium Ja­panese im­ports”.</p>
    <p>He says: “Many Sin­ga­pore­ans travel to Ja­pan, and af­ter ex­pe­ri­enc­ing the amaz­ing flavours there, they re­turn to Sin­ga­pore and seek out these food items again at Ja­panese re­tail­ers across the is­land.”</p>

